			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2010</a> paper:</span><br><i>The Level-Agnostic Modeling Language</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/ColinAtkinson.html">Colin Atkinson</a>, <a href="../profile/BastianKennel.html">Bastian Kennel</a>, <a href="../profile/BjörnGoß.html">Björn Goß</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-19440-5_16">10.1007/978-3-642-19440-5_16</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1a.html"><span class="tagM">T1A: Design</span></a><ul><li> The paper proposes a modeling language designed to abstract over (be agnostic to) specific modeling levels.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3c.html"><span class="tagL">T3C: DSLs</span></a><ul><li> It is a specialized modeling language proposal, aimed at particular modeling practices rather than a general-purpose PL.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1d.html"><span class="tagL">T1D: Composition</span></a><ul><li> It emphasizes bridging/connecting modeling across levels and viewpoints within a unified notation.
</li></ul></li></ul>
